snp3.9:3.5:
“Next come the moths and butterflies
even through the various kinds of ants:
their distinctive mark is produced by birth;
for their kinds differ from one another. (9)

snp3.9:3.6:
“Then know the four-footed beings,
those both small and large:
their distinctive mark is produced by birth;
for their kinds differ from one another. (10)

snp3.9:3.7:
“Know those whose bellies are their feet,
that is, the serpents, those long-backed creatures:
their distinctive mark is produced by birth;
for their kinds differ from one another. (11)

snp3.9:3.8:
“Know too the fish that dwell in water,
whose range is the liquid depths:
their distinctive mark is produced by birth;
for their kinds differ from one another. (12)

snp3.9:3.9:
“Next know the birds,
who fly with their wings in the sky:
their distinctive mark is produced by birth;
for their kinds differ from one another. (13)
[Humans are not intrinsically different from each other]

snp3.9:6.19:
“One who is, like the moon,
stainless, pure, clear, and limpid;
for whom delight in existence is destroyed:
he is the one I call a brahmin. (44)
